    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Introduction</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">The 
                    <ref target="https://wp.lancs.ac.uk/newspainfleets/">New Spain Fleets project</ref> is an ongoing large research endeavour by an interdisciplinary team of archaeologists, historians and computer scientists to delve into the socioeconomic history of the former Spanish empire’s maritime trade. Leveraging Artificial Intelligence methods, we analyse a large historical corpus created in Spain and Mexico between the 16th and 17th centuries.
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">A major challenge for accessing the information in these documents lies in their calligraphy, terminology, and conventions, which require years of specialised training for reading and analysis. This has limited historical research to relatively few scholars, maintaining most of our written heritage still “locked away” in archives.</p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Historical documents from the Spanish colonial era comprise a distinctive set of calligraphies, the most prominent being cortesana, redonda, procesal simple, itálica cursiva, procesal encadenada, and pseudorredonda. These types are found throughout the Spanish colonial archive, often presenting regional variations, particularly in documents created in Mexico 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"i9ZHvW3n","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Murrieta-Flores et al., 2025)","plainCitation":"(Murrieta-Flores et al., 2025)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":1,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/12692394/items/28EENFVL"],"itemData":{"id":1,"type":"article-journal","container-title":"Journal Science and Technology of Archaeological Research","DOI":"https://doi.org/10.1080/20548923.2025.2484828","issue":"1","license":"All rights reserved","title":"Unlocking colonial records with Artificial Intelligence. Achieving the automated transcription of large-scale 16th and 17th-century Latin American historical collections.","volume":"11","author":[{"family":"Murrieta-Flores","given":"Patricia"},{"family":"Vega-Sánchez","given":"Rodrigo"},{"family":"Sánchez-Díaz","given":"Alexander"},{"family":"Cruz-Ríos","given":"Héctor Francisco"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2025"]]}}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Murrieta-Flores et al., 2025).
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Handwritten Text Recognition (HTR) models have been successfully developed for the automatic transcription of historical manuscripts, leveraging Convolutional Neural Networks 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"BEyuAyrF","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Nockels et al., 2022; Ferro et al., 2023)","plainCitation":"(Nockels et al., 2022; Ferro et al., 2023)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":1566,"uris":["http://zotero.org/groups/5238213/items/YZF4RZ6F"],"itemData":{"id":1566,"type":"article-journal","abstract":"Handwritten Text Recognition (HTR) technology is now a mature machine learning tool, becoming integrated in the digitisation processes of libraries and archives, speeding up the transcription of primary sources and facilitating full text searching and analysis of historic texts at scale. However, research into how HTR is changing our information environment is scant. This paper presents a systematic literature review regarding how researchers are using one particular HTR platform, Transkribus, to indicate the domains where HTR is applied, the approach taken, and how the technology is understood. 381 papers from 2015 to 2020 were gathered from Google Scholar, Scopus, and Web of Science, then grouped and coded into categories using quantitative and qualitative approaches. Published research that mentions Transkribus is international and rapidly growing. Transkribus features primarily in archival and library science publications, while a long tail of broad and eclectic disciplines, including history, computer science, citizen science, law and education, demonstrate the wider applicability of the tool. The most common paper categories were humanities applications (67%), technological (25%), users (5%) and tutorials (3%). This paper presents the first overarching review of HTR as featured in published research, while also elucidating how HTR is affecting the information environment.","container-title":"Archival Science","DOI":"10.1007/s10502-022-09397-0","ISSN":"1573-7500","issue":"3","journalAbbreviation":"Arch Sci","language":"en","page":"367-392","source":"Springer Link","title":"Understanding the application of handwritten text recognition technology in heritage contexts: a systematic review of Transkribus in published research","title-short":"Understanding the application of handwritten text recognition technology in heritage contexts","URL":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s10502-022-09397-0","volume":"22","author":[{"family":"Nockels","given":"Joe"},{"family":"Gooding","given":"Paul"},{"family":"Ames","given":"Sarah"},{"family":"Terras","given":"Melissa"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2023",10,23]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2022",9,1]]}}},{"id":1673,"uris":["http://zotero.org/groups/5238213/items/MLP2BVXB"],"itemData":{"id":1673,"type":"article-journal","abstract":"Preserving historical archival heritage involves not only physical measures to safeguard these valuable texts but also providing for their digital preservation. However, merely digitising manuscripts and codexes is not enough. A further step is needed: the digitalisation of their content, i.e. the verbatim transcription of scanned texts. This process enables the accurate preservation of their textual content, making it easier to search for information and conduct further analyses. With the help of artificial intelligence, particularly Deep Neural Networks (DNNs), automatic handwriting recognition can be performed. In this study, we employed a Convolutional Recurrent Neural Network (CRNN), an established type of DNN, to determine the minimum amount of labelled data required to automatically transcribe five different historical datasets that vary in language and time period. The results show that a Character Error Rate (CER) lower than 10% can be achieved with just a few hundred labelled text lines in almost all cases.","container-title":"The International Archives of the Photogrammetry, Remote Sensing and Spatial Information Sciences","DOI":"10.5194/isprs-archives-XLVIII-M-2-2023-557-2023","ISSN":"1682-1750","language":"English","note":"event-title: 29th CIPA Symposium “Documenting, Understanding, Preserving Cultural Heritage. Humanities and Digital Technologies for Shaping the Future” - 25&ndash;30 June 2023, Florence, Italy\npublisher: Copernicus GmbH","page":"557-562","source":"Copernicus Online Journals","title":"AI-ASSISTED DIGITALISATION OF HISTORICAL DOCUMENTS","URL":"https://isprs-archives.copernicus.org/articles/XLVIII-M-2-2023/557/2023/","volume":"XLVIII-M-2-2023","author":[{"family":"Ferro","given":"S."},{"family":"Pelillo","given":"M."},{"family":"Traviglia","given":"A."}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2024",10,8]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2023",6,24]]}}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Nockels et al., 2022; Ferro et al., 2023) although most freely available models have been designed for Northern European languages, and few have only recently become available for Spanish 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"g567zUMw","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Ball et al., 2021; Cu\\uc0\\u233{}llar, 2023b; Coss\\uc0\\u237{}o Olavide, 2023; Cu\\uc0\\u233{}llar, 2023a)","plainCitation":"(Ball et al., 2021; Cuéllar, 2023b; Cossío Olavide, 2023; Cuéllar, 2023a)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":1658,"uris":["http://zotero.org/groups/5238213/items/5B6XM7VV"],"itemData":{"id":1658,"type":"article-journal","abstract":"Samples of Charles V/ Carlos V’s handwriting \n\n\nIt is based upon the book: Rachael Ball and Geoffrey Parker (eds.), Cómo ser rey. Instrucciones del emperador Carlos V a su hijo Felipe. Mayo de 1543. Spanish-English bilingual edition; jointly published with the CSA and The Hispanic Society of America; 2014; ISBN 978-84-15245-45-2. You can find an HTR+-model in Transkribus as of 3 September 2021 named Carlos V/ Charles V – Early modern Spanish – 15th century (1543).\n\n\nThe samples below give an indication how the handwriting of Charles V looked like in 1543. These examples are provided with The Hispanic Society of America’s permission.","DOI":"10.5281/zenodo.5381739","language":"osp","note":"publisher: Zenodo","source":"Zenodo","title":"Sample of Charles V handwriting","URL":"https://zenodo.org/records/5381739","author":[{"family":"Ball","given":"Rachael"},{"family":"Parker","given":"Geoffrey"},{"family":"America","given":"The Hispanic Society","dropping-particle":"of"},{"family":"Romein","given":"Christel Annemieke"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2024",10,9]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2021",9,3]]}}},{"id":1620,"uris":["http://zotero.org/groups/5238213/items/25BEUMZJ"],"itemData":{"id":1620,"type":"software","medium":"Transkribus","title":"Coloso Español","URL":"app.transkribus.org","author":[{"family":"Cuéllar","given":"Álvaro"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2023",7,18]]}}},{"id":1621,"uris":["http://zotero.org/groups/5238213/items/XQD6BX32"],"itemData":{"id":1621,"type":"article-journal","abstract":"Un elevado porcentaje de impresos y manuscritos teatrales del periodo aurisecular no ha sido nunca transcrito en un formato analógico ni, por supuesto, digital. Es imposible, por tanto, emplear estos documentos para realizar búsquedas de nuestro interés o para los valiosos análisis informáticos (estilometría, topic modelling, detección de sentimientos, etc.) que se están desarrollando en los últimos años. Gracias a la Inteligencia Artificial (Transkribus) y técnicas de HTR (Handwritten Text Recognition) he entrenado tres modelos, públicos ya para la comunidad investigadora, capaces de transcribir y modernizar ortográficamente estos documentos de forma automática con un alto grado de precisión: alrededor del 97% de acierto en impresos y 91% en manuscritos. A través de estos modelos he podido procesar unas 1.300 obras teatrales contenidas en impresos y manuscritos procedentes de numerosas bibliotecas, archivos y otras fuentes digitalizadas. Las transcripciones resultantes forman ahora parte del proyecto ETSO, del buscador TEXORO y, además de suponer un avanzado punto de partida para la edición cuidada de los textos, cuentan por sí mismas con la calidad suficiente para ser sometidas a análisis estilométricos, los cuales están arrojando atribuciones autoriales de interés.","container-title":"Hipogrifo. Revista de literatura y cultura del Siglo de Oro","DOI":"10.13035/H.2023.11.01.08","ISSN":"2328-1308","issue":"1","language":"es","license":"Derechos de autor 2023 Hipogrifo. Revista de literatura y cultura del Siglo de Oro","note":"number: 1","page":"101-115","source":"www.revistahipogrifo.com","title":"La Inteligencia Artificial al rescate del Siglo de Oro: transcripción y modernización automática de mil trescientos impresos y manuscritos teatrales","title-short":"La Inteligencia Artificial al rescate del Siglo de Oro","URL":"https://www.revistahipogrifo.com/index.php/hipogrifo/article/view/1262","volume":"11","author":[{"family":"Cuéllar","given":"Álvaro"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2025",1,24]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2023"]]}}},{"id":1640,"uris":["http://zotero.org/groups/5238213/items/DK2YFBAZ"],"itemData":{"id":1640,"type":"post-weblog","abstract":"The purpose of this outreach blog is to document the process of preparing a critical annotated edition of Sancho IV’s Lucidario using digital humanities. It also serves as a tool to promote the application of digital humanities tools for editing medieval texts and of textual criticism. What is the Lucidario? The Lucidario, written...","container-title":"Lucidarios","language":"es","title":"Lucidarios. Editando el <<Lucidario>> de Sancho IV","URL":"https://lucidarios.hypotheses.org/sobre-el-proyecto/about","author":[{"family":"Cossío Olavide","given":"Mario"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2024",12,20]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2023"]]}}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Ball et al., 2021; Cuéllar, 2023b; Cossío Olavide, 2023; Cuéllar, 2023a). However, in our experience, the latter still do not yield accurate transcriptions, either because of being trained for specific sets of documents or too heterogeneous datasets with documents spanning several calligraphies and centuries. Large Spanish models available perform best with late (19th–20th century) documents, their accuracy greatly diminishing when working with earlier documents and “dirty” calligraphies such as procesal simple. To tackle these challenges, we trained specific models, carefully classifying the documents by calligraphy and generating a large sample of human transcription by specialist palaeographers.
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Here, we describe advances and results in developing four accurate HTR models for the automatic transcription of 16th–17th-century Spanish calligraphies: Itálica cursiva, Procesal simple, Redonda, and Procesal encadenada.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Methods</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">We trained both HTR models using Transkribus. The workflow involved 1) the creation of a 170-document corpus classified by calligraphy; 2) uploading the digitised images of the historical documents, obtained from the archives’ websites or manual digitisation; 3) preparing the Ground Truth datasets; 4) training the models; 5) iterating until a Character Error Rate (CER) of &lt;10% on the validation sample was obtained; 6) preparing test datasets and performing accuracy tests. </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Ground Truth refers to the images and the corresponding accurate transcriptions on which a model will learn during training. All transcriptions were carried out manually by a group of palaeographers specialised in New Spain calligraphies. One team member prepared and another revised/corrected literal transcriptions, maintaining spelling, grammar, and punctuation as appeared in the originals, without expanding abbreviations.</p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Historical documents in the Ground Truth datasets (Table 1), currently held in major public archives from Mexico, France, Spain, and the USA, were originally produced in New Spain (today’s Mexico) or Spain between the 16th and 17th centuries. All were written in Spanish, although some contain words (e.g., toponyms) in their original indigenous language, mainly Nahuatl. We only included words in Spanish in the training datasets.</p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">
                    <anchor xml:id="Ref184563683"/>Table 1. Ground Truth datasets.
                </p>
                <table rend="rules">
                    <row>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default"/>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">
                            <hi rend="italic">Itálica cursiva (m3t1)</hi>
                        </cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">
                            <hi rend="italic">Procesal simple (m3t4)</hi>
                        </cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">
                            <p style="text-align: left; ">Redonda</p>
                            <p style="text-align: left; ">(m1t3)</p>
                        </cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">
                            <hi rend="italic">Procesal encadenada (m2t2)</hi>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">Documents</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">40</cell>
