                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">Number of pages</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">339</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">1,148</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">319</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">410</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">Number of lines</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">10,579</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">38,725</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">1,804</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">15,237</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">Number of words</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">106,046</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">258,503</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">21,860</cell>
                        <cell style="text-align: left;" rend="DH-Default">111,807</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">One distinctive aspect of our workflow was adjusting line polygons to ensure they completely encapsulated the letters. Although it has been discussed elsewhere that this process might not always be necessary, this was particularly crucial for the 
                    <hi rend="italic">Procesal simple</hi> calligraphy in which letters usually exceed line limits (Figure 1). We used the adjusted line polygons for training, but all other basic and advanced training settings were set to default in Transkribus (i.e., epochs=100, learning rate=0.0003, batch size=24). The Validation set comprised 10% of the Ground Truth sample.
                </p>
                <figure>
                    <graphic n="1001" width="16.002cm" height="4.266847222222222cm" url="/tmp/tmpee6lvse9/Pictures/c0462addf72d8d7eb8a4a9144ae59841.png" rend="inline"/>
                </figure>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">
                    <anchor xml:id="Ref184447912"/>Figure 1. Adjusting line polygons.
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">We performed accuracy tests for each HTR model using the Transkribus Compute Accuracy tool (Transkribus Expert Client v1.28.0), using documents not included in training or validation. The testing datasets included 60 pages (years 1554 to 1712) for the 
                    <hi rend="italic">Itálica cursiva</hi> model, 35 pages (1590-1608) for the 
                    <hi rend="italic">Procesal simple</hi> model, 21 pages (1570-1580) for the 
                    <hi rend="italic" xml:space="preserve">Redonda </hi>model, and 13 pages (1621) for the 
                    <hi rend="italic">Procesal encadenada</hi> model.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Results</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">The 
                    <hi rend="italic">Itálica cursiva</hi> model was trained on 97 documents from 1536 to 1717. Its first three iterations comprised relatively small datasets (&lt;82,000 words), not achieving the expected CER. The fourth iteration (Itálica_cursiva_m3t1) included over 106,000 words, achieving a CER=8.8% without a base model. Accuracy tests yielded a median CER=7.61% (IQR=13.23%) on the test sample. Text comparisons showed that most automatic transcriptions were accurate, and errors would be negligible to a trained reader (
                    <hi rend="italic">Figure 2</hi>). Furthermore, a comparison with the largest freely available HTR model for Spanish (Coloso Español, CER=4.8%) showed that our model significantly outperforms the former (CER=23.70% ColEsp vs 15.97% ItalCur_m3t1).
                </p>
                <figure>
                    <graphic n="1002" width="16.002cm" height="9.017cm" url="/tmp/tmpee6lvse9/Pictures/b3abc46edd46730ecd9dad81d6b53d10.png" rend="inline"/>
                </figure>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">
                    <anchor xml:id="Ref184449965"/>Figure 2. Text comparison for an Italica cursiva HTR transcription.
                    <lb/>The test only highlights those words where Ground Truth (green) and HTR (red) differ.
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">The 
                    <hi rend="italic">Procesal simple</hi> HTR model was trained on over 80 documents from 1512 to 1657, involving nine iterations. The last iteration (Procesal_simple_m3t4) included an accumulated sample of 258,503 words, achieving a CER=8.92%. Accuracy tests showed a median CER=16.72% (IQR=12.23%). This higher CER was affected by two factors. First, image resolution: low-resolution images from an archive’s website (≤1.24 MP, n=17) yielded significantly higher CERs than manually digitised images (8.41 MP, n=18) (median=26.04% vs 14.53%, p&lt;0.001, Figure 3). The negative effect of image resolution on model recognition accuracy has long been reported and continues to be an important challenge in character recognition 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"ZJJMXZe3","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Jacobs et al., 2005; Baek et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2020)","plainCitation":"(Jacobs et al., 2005; Baek et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2020)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":2123,"uris":["http://zotero.org/groups/5680011/items/BJKLQUCB"],"itemData":{"id":2123,"type":"paper-conference","abstract":"Cheap and versatile cameras make it possible to easily and quickly capture a wide variety of documents. However, low resolution cameras present a challenge to OCR because it is virtually impossible to do character segmentation independently from recognition. In this paper we solve these problems simultaneously by applying methods borrowed from cursive handwriting recognition. To achieve maximum robustness, we use a machine learning approach based on a convolutional neural network. When our system is combined with a language model using dynamic programming, the overall performance is in the vicinity of 80-95% word accuracy on pages captured with a 1024x768 webcam and 10-point text.","collection-title":"ICDAR '05","container-title":"Proceedings of the Eighth International Conference on Document Analysis and Recognition","DOI":"10.1109/ICDAR.2005.233","event-place":"USA","ISBN":"978-0-7695-2420-7","page":"695–699","publisher":"IEEE Computer Society","publisher-place":"USA","source":"ACM Digital Library","title":"Text Recognition of Low-resolution Document Images","URL":"https://doi.org/10.1109/ICDAR.2005.233","author":[{"family":"Jacobs","given":"Charles"},{"family":"Simard","given":"Patrice Y."},{"family":"Viola","given":"Paul"},{"family":"Rinker","given":"James"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2025",4,30]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2005"]],"season":"Agosto"}}},{"id":1902,"uris":["http://zotero.org/groups/5680011/items/5T6L49Q4"],"itemData":{"id":1902,"type":"article","abstract":"Many new proposals for scene text recognition (STR) models have been introduced in recent years. While each claim to have pushed the boundary of the technology, a holistic and fair comparison has been largely missing in the field due to the inconsistent choices of training and evaluation datasets. This paper addresses this difficulty with three major contributions. First, we examine the inconsistencies of training and evaluation datasets, and the performance gap results from inconsistencies. Second, we introduce a unified four-stage STR framework that most existing STR models fit into. Using this framework allows for the extensive evaluation of previously proposed STR modules and the discovery of previously unexplored module combinations. Third, we analyze the module-wise contributions to performance in terms of accuracy, speed, and memory demand, under one consistent set of training and evaluation datasets. Such analyses clean up the hindrance on the current comparisons to understand the performance gain of the existing modules.","DOI":"10.48550/arXiv.1904.01906","note":"arXiv:1904.01906","number":"arXiv:1904.01906","publisher":"arXiv","source":"arXiv.org","title":"What Is Wrong With Scene Text Recognition Model Comparisons? Dataset and Model Analysis","title-short":"What Is Wrong With Scene Text Recognition Model Comparisons?","URL":"http://arxiv.org/abs/1904.01906","author":[{"family":"Baek","given":"Jeonghun"},{"family":"Kim","given":"Geewook"},{"family":"Lee","given":"Junyeop"},{"family":"Park","given":"Sungrae"},{"family":"Han","given":"Dongyoon"},{"family":"Yun","given":"Sangdoo"},{"family":"Oh","given":"Seong Joon"},{"family":"Lee","given":"Hwalsuk"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2025",4,30]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2019",12,18]]}}},{"id":1901,"uris":["http://zotero.org/groups/5680011/items/NN9F2XS4"],"itemData":{"id":1901,"type":"article","abstract":"Low-resolution text images are often seen in natural scenes such as documents captured by mobile phones. Recognizing low-resolution text images is challenging because they lose detailed content information, leading to poor recognition accuracy. An intuitive solution is to introduce super-resolution (SR) techniques as pre-processing. However, previous single image super-resolution (SISR) methods are trained on synthetic low-resolution images (e.g.Bicubic down-sampling), which is simple and not suitable for real low-resolution text recognition. To this end, we pro-pose a real scene text SR dataset, termed TextZoom. It contains paired real low-resolution and high-resolution images which are captured by cameras with different focal length in the wild. It is more authentic and challenging than synthetic data, as shown in Fig. 1. We argue improv-ing the recognition accuracy is the ultimate goal for Scene Text SR. In this purpose, a new Text Super-Resolution Network termed TSRN, with three novel modules is developed. (1) A sequential residual block is proposed to extract the sequential information of the text images. (2) A boundary-aware loss is designed to sharpen the character boundaries. (3) A central alignment module is proposed to relieve the misalignment problem in TextZoom. Extensive experiments on TextZoom demonstrate that our TSRN largely improves the recognition accuracy by over 13%of CRNN, and by nearly 9.0% of ASTER and MORAN compared to synthetic SR data. Furthermore, our TSRN clearly outperforms 7 state-of-the-art SR methods in boosting the recognition accuracy of LR images in TextZoom. For example, it outperforms LapSRN by over 5% and 8%on the recognition accuracy of ASTER and CRNN. Our results suggest that low-resolution text recognition in the wild is far from being solved, thus more research effort is needed.","DOI":"10.48550/arXiv.2005.03341","note":"arXiv:2005.03341","number":"arXiv:2005.03341","publisher":"arXiv","source":"arXiv.org","title":"Scene Text Image Super-Resolution in the Wild","URL":"http://arxiv.org/abs/2005.03341","author":[{"family":"Wang","given":"Wenjia"},{"family":"Xie","given":"Enze"},{"family":"Liu","given":"Xuebo"},{"family":"Wang","given":"Wenhai"},{"family":"Liang","given":"Ding"},{"family":"Shen","given":"Chunhua"},{"family":"Bai","given":"Xiang"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2025",4,30]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2020",8,2]]}}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Jacobs et al., 2005; Baek et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2020). Second, calligraphy “neatness”: A subset of documents with clearer calligraphy yielded even lower CERs than those in the validation sample (median=6.1%, IQR=2.04%).
                </p>
                <figure>
                    <anchor xml:id="Ref184447296"/>
                    <graphic n="1003" width="16.002cm" height="7.189611111111111cm" url="/tmp/tmpee6lvse9/Pictures/eb90093b9c3312e49713158e70cfb8ba.png" rend="inline"/>
                </figure>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Figure 3. Impact of image resolution on the 
                    <hi rend="italic">Procesal simple</hi> model accuracy.
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">The 
                    <hi rend="italic">Redonda</hi> and 
                    <hi rend="italic">Procesal Encadenada</hi> models are our latest developments. The 
                    <hi rend="italic">Redonda</hi> model was trained on twelve documents from 1536 to 1576. Although it was a relatively small dataset, the homogeneity and clarity of this calligraphy style allowed the model to achieve a CER=5.25% when trained with the 
                    <hi rend="italic">Procesal Simple</hi> as a base model. 
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">The 
                    <hi rend="italic">Procesal Encadenada</hi> model recognises a particularly challenging calligraphy. It required the preparation of a large training set by a group of expert palaeographers, comprising over 111,000 words in documents from 1590 to 1640. Leveraging the 
                    <hi rend="italic">Procesal Simple</hi> as base model, the model achieved a CER=7.80% on the validation set. Accuracy tests showed a median CER=18.17% (IQR=6.23%) on the testing set while also confirming its outperformance of the largest freely available model, Coloso Español, on this sample (CER=33.55%, IQR=6.94).
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Conclusions</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">We developed HTR models for 
                    <hi rend="italic" xml:space="preserve">Itálica cursiva, Procesal simple, Redonda, </hi>and 
                    <hi rend="italic">Procesal encadenada</hi> calligraphies (CER=8.8%, 8.92%, 5.25%, and 7.80%, respectively), four of the most prevalent in 16
                    <hi rend="superscript">th</hi>-17
                    <hi rend="superscript">th</hi>-century Spanish historical documents. The models provide sufficiently accurate transcriptions, allowing users to read the text fluidly, requiring minor corrections. Considering the significant effect of image quality on models’ accuracy, users and cultural heritage institutions should work with high-resolution images whenever possible. Our models will soon become publicly available as outputs of the New Spain Fleets project, allowing interested audiences to access vast amounts of historical information so far locked behind challenging Spanish American calligraphies.
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
